Name: Graham, Lindsey
text:
The Senate Republican Conference just had a good discussion about the Big Beautiful Bill.
¬†
Those who criticize the bill for not reducing spending enough ‚Äì I understand your point and I agree. To those who believe we must pass some version of the bill by July 4th, you‚Äôre dead right.
¬†
Making the tax cuts permanent, increasing defense spending and providing money to secure our border is an essential part of this bill, and it needs to be passed now.
¬†
When it comes to spending reductions, here‚Äôs the reality:
¬†
‚úÖ The reconciliation process is focused only on mandatory spending. By law, changes to Social Security cannot be a part of reconciliation.
¬†
‚úÖ Medicare has been virtually untouched in both the House and Senate proposals. Medicaid reforms like work requirements and dealing with the provider tax scam are sources of legitimate savings without reducing benefits for those who need it. Medicaid spending has grown by nearly 50% in the last 5 years and it is now time to address this problem.
¬†
‚úÖ We can improve this bill in terms of cost savings. But it‚Äôs important to note we have two more reconciliation bills available to us to reduce spending further and define additional tax cuts. 
¬†
My goal: Make this bill better in a way the House can accept and put it on President @realDonaldTrump‚Äôs desk by July 4th.

Name: Begich, Nicholas J.
text:
There is a great deal of confusion around the OBBBA. The Congressional Budget Office (CBO) scored growth over the next 10 years at 1.8%. At no point in modern history has the United States experienced such low growth as is projected by the CBO.¬†¬†

Consider this:

- The Atlanta Fed‚Äôs most recent GDP estimate for Q2 is 4.6%!
- We are in the middle of an AI revolution.
- We are on the cusp of a robotics revolution.
- We have 8 Trillion dollars of new investment committed to the U.S. over the new several years. To put this into context, the U.S. GDP is approximately 28 Trillion, making this incremental investment commitment so large it actually dwarfs the entire 10 year CBO growth projection on its own.

The bottom line is that the CBO scoring for GDP is clearly flawed, and is being used to mislead the public. The One Big Beautiful Bill is pro-growth, responsible legislation that helps put us on a better track. 

Yes, more work is needed to address the deficit and debt - urgent issues. This is the beginning of that process, and it is a STRONG start.

Name: Mullin, Markwayne
text:
Most Americans get the mission behind President Trump's historic 'One Big, Beautiful Bill.' But, there's been some back and forth.

Here's what you need to know ‚¨áÔ∏è

FACT: President Trump's 'One Big, Beautiful Bill' was designed by the President himself, his team, and his closest MAGA allies in Congress to deliver the MAGA agenda. 

This is the President's vision.

No bill is perfect, but we have a once-in-a-lifetime bill to deliver EXACTLY what @POTUS promised: lower taxes, a secure border, strong military, and reining in spending. And with only 51 votes!

It's simple: President Trump won HUGE in November. He helped us deliver a House and Senate GOP majority. It's our job to help him deliver the MAGA agenda.

As we speak, many of us are still working with the White House on improving this bill in the Senate. 

Keep in mind: this reconciliation process can ONLY be used for non-discretionary (aka mandatory) spending. Stick with me. All that means is because President Trump's MAGA bill only requires 51 votes vs 60, there are strict limits on what can be included.

The appropriations process is how we can aggressively cut more discretionary spending (already in the works). Plus, we've got the rescissions process (@WhiteHouse sends Congress a package of funding to cut) to make @DOGE cuts permanent.

It's a lot of government lingo, but we'll do our best to keep breaking it down. Bottom line: trust President Trump. He made a lot of promises on the trail, and this bill delivers.

Name: Bishop, Sanford D.
text:
Today, Congressman Brett Guthrie (KY-02) and I, the co-chairs of the bipartisan Congressional Job Corps Caucus, led a letter signed by 199 members of Congress to U.S. Department of Labor Secretary Lori Chavez-DeRemer urging her to continue the Job Corps program. On May 29, the Department of Labor issued a notice that it will begin a phased pause in operations at contractor-operated Job Corps centers across the country. Job Corps is a national program with over 120 centers across the country. Job Corps offers at-risk youth varied academic opportunities and career pathways in business and industry.
Nearly 20,000 young people utilize Job Corps to learn skills for in-demand vocational and technical job training. Job Corps is one of the few national programs that specifically targets the 16-24-year-old population that is neither working, nor in school, and provides them with a direct pathway into employment openings in industries such as manufacturing and shipbuilding. The program also connects these young Americans with apprenticeships, higher education opportunities, or the military. https://t.co/CKWPrP2Viq

Name: Stutzman, Marlin A.
text: When we arrived in Damascus, we observed grown men openly weeping and others cheering as they saw their homeland for the first time in decades. For centuries, Syria boasted a diverse, multi-cultural population until the 54-year reign of the Assad regime.

Name: Stutzman, Marlin A.
text: During our visit, we witnessed the devastated Syrian economy, where cash is almost worthless and credit cards are not accepted. Open-air markets resort to basic barter and trade for items like clothing and necessities, which are laid out next to rubble. With no functioning gas stations, young men with large hand-held jugs stand along the road to fill vehicles for a price negotiated on the spot.

Name: Stutzman, Marlin A.
text: We then met individually with Syria‚Äôs new president, Ahmed al-Sharaa, well aware of his previous history as a Syrian Al-Qaeda member, though having cut ties in 2016. However, contrary to his biography, the actions al-Sharaa has taken to help the country so far have been positive. https://t.co/6VAPG86DC4

Name: Stutzman, Marlin A.
text: In our meetings, al-Sharaa expressed a desire to work with the West. He called Israel by name and simultaneously emphasized his desire to promote peace and even possibly join the Abraham Accords. His commitment to avoid the often alluring proxy relationship with Iran is a testament to his desire to find more favorable partners. America is accustomed to being asked for funds and military support, but al-Sharaa wants Syrians defending Syria.

Name: Stutzman, Marlin A.
text: Hearing al-Sharaa and the Syrian government express an interest in being a stabilizing force in the region for peace and prosperity is a moment in time we must consider carefully, and why we applaud President Trump‚Äôs decision to lift the sanctions on a war-weary Syria. For accountability, we also believe al-Sharaa must be willing to accept international investigations into the treatment of Syria‚Äôs religious minorities.

On June 6, 1944, 156,000 American, British, and Canadian troops launched the largest amphibious assault in history on the beaches of Normandy‚Äîa pivotal moment in World War II that helped turn the tide against tyranny.

In the 24 hours we now remember as D-Day, more than 4,000 Allied soldiers, sailors, airmen, and coastguardsmen gave their lives in the name of freedom.

The greatest tribute we can offer to their sacrifice is to uphold and strengthen the democratic ideals for which they fought.

On this monumental day, we pause to honor the brave souls who fought for our freedom.

Eighty-one years ago, America and our allies united in a daring effort to liberate an entire continent from tyranny. It was a moment of courage, conviction, and sacrifice that forever altered the course of history.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Today, on D-Day, we remember the heroes who charged the beaches of Normandy‚Äîordinary men who carried out extraordinary acts to liberate the world from tyranny. Their bravery reshaped history and secured freedom for generations to come.
 
Last year, I had the profound honor of standing on those hallowed shores for the 80th anniversary‚Äîan experience I will carry with me for the rest of my life. I stood among living legends, listened to their stories, thanked them for their sacrifice, and witnessed a global outpouring of gratitude.
 
While there, I had the privilege of presenting my dear friend Mae Krier of Levittown‚Äî98 years young‚Äîwith the Congressional Gold Medal. Mae is one of the millions of women who answered the call during WWII. Through my bipartisan Rosie the Riveter Congressional Gold Medal Act, now signed into law, we honor the more than 6 million women like Mae who strengthened our nation from the home front and helped make victory possible.
 
On this 81st anniversary, may we all pause to say thank you‚Äîto the men who stormed the cliffs, the women who built the arsenal of democracy, and every hero who stepped forward in defense of freedom.
 
We are forever in your debt.

Name: Donalds, Byron
text:
Executive Order: "Deploying Advanced Nuclear Reactor Technologies for National Security"

Description: "What this executive order will do is speed-up the approval and adoption process for specialized nuclear reactors at [defense and AI installations]. It also involves @ENERGY making available the necessary fuel stock. It also creates a special envoy position and a strategy around nuclear technology export‚Äìthe idea being that we can grow American industry on the back of foreign purchasers who are interested in this sort of technology as well." ‚Äì @willscharf

Name: Donalds, Byron
text:
Executive Order: "Reforming Nuclear Reactor Testing at @ENERGY"

Description: "This next executive order relates to nuclear reactor testing...The degree of overregulation and governmental inaction in this space in particular has had the effect of throttling development of new highly-modernized nuclear reactors that could really revolutionize the field of nuclear power ¬†generation. So this executive order orders a revised regulatory process to speed this whole process while preserving obviously core safety concerns. It also creates a new pilot program with an expectation that we will have three new experimental reactors by 7/4 next year." ‚Äì @willscharf

Name: Donalds, Byron
text:
Executive Order: "Ordering the Reform of the @NRCgov"

Description: "This next executive order is intended to reform the Nuclear Regulatory Commission. You heard a few of the people here speak about the complex regulatory processes that have really held the nuclear industry back. Before 1978, there were 133 reactors built in the United States. Since 1978, only two new commercial reactors have come online. That's because of overregulation and the goal of this executive order is bringing that regulatory process into line with the actual needs of the industry and public safety, with an end goal of quadrupling the amount of nuclear power production in the next two and a half decades." ‚Äì¬†@willscharf

Name: Donalds, Byron
text:
Executive Order: "Reinvigorating the Nuclear Industrial Base"

Description: "Lastly...we have an executive order on reinvigorating the nuclear industrial base. There are a number of core issues here including the issue with fuel feedstock that one of the speakers mentioned before. This executive order among other actions includes an invocation of the defense production act in order to spur closer collaboration with private industry to ensure that we have the fuel supplies we need for a modernized nuclear energy sector. In addition to that, it includes crucial provisions relating to the development of the nuclear energy sector workforce and a number of other key building blocks to the overall nuclear industry that we are trying to spur here." ‚Äì @willscharf

Name: Donalds, Byron
text: .@SecretaryBurgum: "This is a huge day for the nuclear industry. Mark this day on your calendar. This is going to turn the clock back on over 50 years of overregulation of an industry. American greatness has always come from innovation and we were very innovative. We led post-WWII in all things nuclear, but then, we've been stagnated. We choked it with overregulation. Today, Will is going to walk us through a series of four executive orders, each of these help attack separate issues that have held back this industry...but also a big change."

Name: Donalds, Byron
text: .@SecDef: "Energy security is national security. If we don't have reliable energy for our basing, for our troops, whether forward-deployed or domestically, we're vulnerable. So by having small modular nuclear capabilities, which are rapidly being fielded, that we can use on our bases here and around the world, we're creating an environment where if things happen elsewhere, the military can be relied-upon...Also, we're including artificial intelligence in everything we do. If we don't, we're not fast enough, we're not keeping up with adversaries. You need the energy to fuel it, nuclear is a huge part of that, modular or otherwise. So, we're going to have the lights-on, and AI operating when others do not, faster than everybody else because of nuclear capabilities, so this is a big game change for us as well."

Meanwhile, there has been very little real progress on bringing the hostages home. And our President's inflammatory rhetoric, including calling for the displacement of millions of Palestinians, has only fueled the illegal visions of some of the most right-wing parties in Israel. 

We need to bring all the hostages home. And Palestinians in Gaza need safe access to food and water. Israel and Hamas must agree to a lasting ceasefire, and treat it with the urgency it deserves. Name: Weber, Randy K. Sr.
text:
Eighty-one years ago, to this day, the young and most vital of our nation stormed the beaches of Normandy, France, to liberate the European Continent from authoritarian fascism. As these young men meticulously prepared for their invasion, they recognized the hardship and sacrifice that lay ahead. Nevertheless, the young men understood the importance of defending the traditions of individuality and freedom in the West; that is why, when confronted with insurmountable odds on the beaches of Omaha and Utah, these young men and their commanders refused to turn back, instead running forward into the breach carrying a beacon of hope and freedom to the world.¬†

We shall never forget what took place that day and the heroes who took part. We will continue to honor their courage and sacrifice against all odds. Particularly the bravery of young Texans from the 14th District, whose actions continue to serve as an example of perseverance and hope today. Here are two quotes from folks in Southeast Texas during D-Day.¬†

¬†‚ÄúAs the sky lightened, the armada became visible. The smoking and burning French shoreline also became more defined. At 0600, the huge guns of the Allied navies opened up with what must have been one of the greatest artillery barrages ever. The diesels on board our craft failed to muffle the tornadic blasting. I could see the TEXAS firing broadside into the coastline. Boom-ba-ba-boom-ba-ba-boom! Within minutes, giant swells from the recoil of those guns nearly swamped us and added to the seasickness and misery. But one could also actually see the two-thousand-pound missiles tumbling on their targets.‚Äù ‚Äì Sergeant Robert Bixler, 116th Infantry Regiment, 29th Infantry Division.

‚ÄúThe ramp was lowered immediately after the rockets fired. It was our hope and desire to run right up on the beach for a dry landing, not because we were afraid of getting wet but because if we were soaked it would be added weight to carry while climbing. The British Navy man had promised to put us down dry, but suddenly we ran aground with the ramp dropped. The officer said, ‚ÄòEverybody out.‚Äô Looking ahead, I could see fifteen or twenty feet of water, a muddy dirty gray stretch. The Entire area was marked by craters, shell holes from the guns on the TEXAS and the bombers.‚Äù ‚Äì Lieutenant George Kerchner, 2nd Ranger Battalion.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we recognize members of our community who embody the very best of the American spirit‚Äîthose whose character and tireless devotion to others remind us of the values that have always made our nation great. Today, we honor a woman whose life is a testament to service, sacrifice, and unwavering love of country. Meet this week‚Äôs Hometown Hero: the incomparable Connie Whalen.
 
Connie has worn many titles‚ÄîU.S. Navy Counselor, Executive Director of the Guardians of Washington Crossing National Cemetery, @TMFoundation mentor, and community leader. But above all, she is a faithful steward of duty, honor, and country.
 
At just 17 years old, Connie answered the call to serve and enlisted in the United States Navy. Over the next 21 years, she built a distinguished military career as a Navy Counselor. Her record of excellence earned her the National Defense Service Medal, Navy & Marine Corps Achievement Medal, Global War on Terrorism Service Medal, three Naval Meritorious Service Medals, and an extraordinary 25 Gold Wreath Awards for outstanding recruiting contributions during three of our nation‚Äôs most pivotal military operations‚Äîthe Persian Gulf War, Operation Enduring Freedom, and Operation Iraqi Freedom.
 
But retirement didn‚Äôt mark the end of Connie‚Äôs service‚Äîit marked the beginning of a new mission, every bit as meaningful.
 
As Executive Director of the Guardians of the National Cemetery at Washington Crossing, Connie leads a devoted team of volunteers who carry out one of our nation‚Äôs most sacred responsibilities: honoring those who served. From organizing memorial ceremonies and greeting funeral processions to offering final salutes and ensuring every veteran is laid to rest with dignity‚Äîthey are present, steadfast, and reverent. In every kind of weather, they stand watch. And on the final Thursday of each month, they hold a solemn ceremony for veterans with no family present. Under Connie‚Äôs leadership, the Guardians carry out sacred acts of remembrance that ensure no veteran‚Äîand no family‚Äîis ever overlooked, unhonored, or forgotten. Every life is acknowledged, every sacrifice remembered, and every service met with the gratitude it deserves.
 
As a leader with the Travis Manion Foundation, Connie plays a central role in shaping the next generation through the ‚ÄúCharacter Does Matter‚Äù program. Across our community and region, she mentors students and instills in them the values that define true leadership‚Äîintegrity, courage, respect, service, and a deep love of country. She encourages them to honor our veterans, serve their communities, and live lives rooted in character and purpose. Whether organizing service projects, building tributes to those who served, or guiding young people to lead by example, Connie empowers our next generation to become citizens who give more than they take.
 
I‚Äôve had the distinct honor of working alongside Connie over the years, and I‚Äôve seen firsthand the heart and dedication she brings to everything she does. She gives of herself fully‚Äîto our veterans, our youth, and our community‚Äîasks for nothing in return, and delivers more than most could imagine.
 
Connie, thank you‚Äîfor your courage, mentorship, leadership, and love of this country. You are, in every sense, a true Hometown Hero.

On June 6, 1944, more than 150,000 Allied troops launched the largest amphibious invasion in history. Leading the assault was General Omar Bradley, a proud Missouri native from Randolph County, whose steady leadership helped turn the tide of the war. He went on to command over 1.3 million troops and retired as our nation‚Äôs last five-star General.

Over 9,000 young men gave their lives or were wounded that day to secure freedom for millions. Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
President Reagan‚Äôs ‚ÄúBoys of Pointe du Hoc,‚Äù eloquently spoken in 1984 from the same cliffs where US Army Rangers achieved the impossible 40 years earlier.

Their mission: silence the German guns aimed at the Allied landings below. Pointe du Hoc was a strategic stronghold, perched between Utah and Omaha Beach, fortified with artillery and machine guns that could‚Äôve shredded the invasion before it even started.

So before the main force hit the beach, 225 Army Rangers set out. They were led by a Texan and Aggie‚ÄîLieutenant Colonel James Earl Rudder. Under heavy fire, they fired rocket-propelled grappling hooks and scaled the 100-foot cliff. When they reached the top, they found the guns had been moved. But the mission didn‚Äôt stop there.

The Rangers searched, found the artillery, destroyed it, and held the line against fierce German counterattacks. For two straight days, they fought outnumbered and isolated.

When the battle was over, only 90 Rangers remained.
Rudder had been wounded twice and refused to leave. For his actions, he received the Distinguished Service Cross‚Äîthe second-highest award for combat valor. In 2022, the surviving Rangers were awarded the Congressional Gold Medal.

They didn‚Äôt climb that cliff for medals. They did it because it had to be done. They showed what courage, sacrifice, and American grit look like.

--
Courtesy @Reagan_Library @RonaldReagan

Name: McCormick, David
text:
On the 81st Anniversary of D-Day, let us remember Pennsylvanian, @USArmy paratrooper, and Easy Company Commander, Major Richard ‚ÄòDick‚Äô Winters, who wrote his 10 Rules of Leadership after Band of Brothers was published. These rules have guided my service in the Army, my business career, and my time serving Pennsylvania in the US Senate. ‚¨áÔ∏èüá∫üá∏

1. Strive to be a leader of character competence, and courage.

2. Lead from the front. Say ‚ÄúFollow me!‚Äù and then lead the way.

3. Stay in top physical shape ‚Äì physical stamina is the root of mental toughness.

4. Develop your team. If you know your people, are fair in setting realistic goals and expectations, and lead by example, you will develop teamwork.

5. Delegate responsibility to your subordinates and let them do their jobs. You can‚Äôt do a good job if you don‚Äôt have a chance to use your imagination or your creativity.

6. Anticipate problems and prepare to overcome obstacles. Don‚Äôt wait until you get to the top of the ridge and then make up your mind.

7. Remain humble. Don‚Äôt worry about who receives the credit. Never let power or authority go to your head.

8. Take a moment of self-reflection. Look at yourself in the mirror every night and ask yourself if you did your best.

9. True satisfaction comes from getting the job done. The key to a successful leader is to earn respect ‚Äì not because of rank or position, but because you are a leader of character.

10. Hang tough! Never, ever, give up.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
3. The Byrd Rule

Named after Senator Robert Byrd, the Byrd rule is a mechanism to decide what makes it through reconciliation.

Only changes that directly affect taxes, spending, and revenue can be included. 

If it‚Äôs mostly about changing policy and doesn‚Äôt really impact the budget, it should be kicked out.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
2. You‚Äôre going to hear the word reconciliation.

Reconciliation is essentially a budget. Except you don‚Äôt need 60 votes in the Senate for it to pass‚Äì you only need 51.

There is a catch‚Ä¶.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
Any senator can challenge any aspect of the bill for not complying with the Byrd Rule. 

The decider is the Senate Parliamentarian, Elizabeth MacDonough.

Name: Landsman, Greg

Name: Kiley, Kevin
text:
In the last year I set out to reverse 10 of Governor Newsom's most harmful policies. We've made significant progress:

1) Gas-Car Ban: My Resolution to reverse the ban passed the House and Senate with bipartisan support.

2) Illegal Health Care: We forced Newsom to end his free Medi-Cal for illegal immigrants policy.

3) Out-of-Control Crime: Our initiative to make crime illegal again, Prop. 36, was passed overwhelmingly by California voters.

4) Homelessness: The Supreme Court ruled in our favor and against Newsom, reversing the 9th Circuit and allowing local communities to clear encampments.

5) High-Speed Rail: The federal government is cutting off funding after the Department of Transportation audit, which we announced in February, found California woefully out of compliance.

6) Sanctuary State: My bill to end sanctuary policies has significant traction, and the combination of executive actions and federal law enforcement has mitigated the sanctuary policy.

7) Water Scarcity: We've secured major funding for the first new significant water storage in California in decades, and we're stopping the diversion of water to the ocean.

8) Catastrophic wildfires: We've passed the Fix Our Forests Act through the House with bipartisan support.

9) Failing Schools: The House just passed the most significant school choice legislation in history, which I sponsored. It is part of the reconciliation bill that will receive a vote in the Senate.

10) Election Chaos: The SAVE Act, a bill I've sponsored to require proof of citizenship to register to vote, has passed the House with bipartisan support.

üßµ¬†I am working with @RepAaronBean to codify a key Trump action to effectively eliminate improper and fraudulent payments.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:

Name: Ernst, Joni
text: In addition to the $79 billion stolen in COVID relief, it is conservatively estimated that tens of billions in improper payments would continue to occur every year in the future without proper safeguards.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
Including asking:
¬†
Is the Social Security Number valid?
¬†
Does the name on the application match the Social Security Number?
¬†
Does the date of birth on the application match the Social Security Number?

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
We cannot continue to sit idly by while taxpayers are ripped off and America's veterans are left behind because of bureaucratic incompetence.
¬†
Thankfully, President Trump took action.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text: Beyond the astronomical cost to taxpayers, a new report revealed how ongoing improper payment issues resulted in veterans with serious disabilities, like amputations, being short-changed anywhere from $132.74 to $4,170.59 in their monthly disability checks.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
Through an executive order, President Trump created a commonsense process to effectively eliminate all improper payments.
¬†
But we cannot allow this to be a temporary solution.
¬†
It must be codified by Congress and made permanent.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text: As leaders of the Senate and House DOGE Caucus, @RepAaronBean and I have introduced the Delivering On Government Efficiency in Spending Act to do just that.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:

¬†

¬†
I will continue leading the way.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text: In addition to the preventative measure, every expenditure will be made available for public inspection on the @usaspending website -¬†with annual updates for ongoing transactions.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:

This ensures accuracy and eligibility.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Join me in congratulating Willard Tresler of Troop 34, from New Hope, on earning the rank of Eagle Scout! 

For his project, Willard created and installed an American flag retirement drop box for Solebury Township, ensuring our community has a proper and respectful way to retire worn flags. He also taught flag etiquette to both his Boy Scout troop and a local Girl Scout troop, designed and distributed educational pamphlets, and hosted a formal Flag Retirement Ceremony.

The project brought together more than 30 volunteers and over 200 hours of work, and was completed in memory of Mr. William ‚ÄúBill‚Äù Tinsman, a Navy Veteran, responsible for flying the American flag beneath the Lumberville foot bridge‚Äîa tradition he started in September of 2001 and continued for over 22 years.

Scout ceremonies are more than celebrations‚Äîthey‚Äôre a chance to listen, connect, and learn. Talking with Scouts like Willard, their families, and dedicated troop leaders offers a valuable window into the heart of our community. Thank you all for the work you do to lead, guide, and serve.

On June 14, 1777, our young nation adopted a flag not just as a symbol, but as a statement: that liberty, unity, and sacrifice would define who we are. 

Every year, I‚Äôm honored to join the Fairless Hills Elks Lodge #2023 for their annual Flag Day ceremony‚Äîan event that keeps that spirit alive in Bucks County. The Elks have been proud stewards of patriotism and service since 1868, and I‚Äôve long been proud to partner with them in honoring our history, supporting our veterans, and investing in our next generation of leaders.

This year‚Äôs ceremony celebrated that tradition by recognizing individuals who exemplify service and excellence. Congratulations to scholarship recipients Eric Jean, Erica Logue, and Laila Waters, and to Officer of the Year Jamie Lombardo! And big thanks to Lodge #2023 for all you do for our community and making this annual tradition a powerful reminder of what it means to be an American.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text:
Second -- the U.S. military is one of the most trusted institutions in America. Using them at home in law enforcement roles is the fastest way to kill that trust.

We know this from experience in Michigan. In 1967, the National Guard was deployed to Detroit in response to protests at our then-Governor‚Äôs request. It made the violence worse, and the scars are still there 60 years later.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text: It's hard to make the case that this deployment is about public safety instead of politics, when law enforcement leaders did not request the military to intervene.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text: First -- Our troops are intended by law to protect America from foreign adversaries, never to advance one party's political agenda. This is what separates American democracy from places like Chinese communism.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text: I have been focused on this issue since day one because President Trump sought to use the military against American citizens in his first term. I've asked Secretary Hegseth, the Chairman of the Joint Chiefs, and other Pentagon officials about this point explicitly during their nomination hearings, because officials from Trump‚Äôs first cabinet, such as former Secretary Mark Esper, wrote first-hand accounts of convincing the president against such actions.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text:
Third -- and connected to the above point, our troops are not trained in law enforcement tactics. The Secretary of the Army reaffirmed this fact to me during his nomination hearing in January. 

The military is trained to carry out high-intensity foreign combat, like house-to-house counterterrorism operations. And they do that exceptionally well. But this does not always translate to things like crowd control and urban policing, which can escalate quickly if not properly trained.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa

Name: Greene, Marjorie Taylor
text:
Hi David, I think the AI discussion is one of the most important issues we can plan for.
For context of my background and conceptual framework. As a business owner in construction, I am pro business and understand the labor issues and needs better than most.
As a Representative in the U.S. House, I believe protecting federalism is essential, constitutional, and the American way.
Every innovative industry in our country‚Äôs history has had to rise under each states ability to regulate and make laws on behalf of their citizens. 
Tying our states hands behind their back for 10 years with a moratorium freezing states ability to regulate and make laws is the opposite of federalism and makes us no different than China with a big government power grab.
Allowing states to regulate and make laws will preserve the state‚Äôs abilities to choose their path.
Currently on the federal level, Congress has not developed a federal regulatory plan for AI yet. We would be preemptively destroying federalism for 10 years without a plan.
We know governors and states are ranked on job creation and economic stats.
By protecting federalism, some states will compete to be the most AI friendly and will make decisions to recruit AI tech companies with varieties of incentives.
Other states may choose to be less AI friendly and that‚Äôs their right.
My district is a filled with wonderful working class people. 
Many of whom will have their jobs replaced by AI and AI driven robotics. 
I‚Äôve watched Georgia‚Äôs rural communities devastated for the last 40 years after manufacturing jobs were sent overseas and once those plants shut down, other jobs were scarce.
This destroyed small towns, their economies, and consequently it destroyed families as well. 
How many human jobs will AI replace over the next 10 years? 
It‚Äôs predicted to replace a large swath of human jobs in many areas.
And once AI replaces all of those human jobs, they will not have hardly any jobs to find.
My district has an unemployment rate of 2.9% but after AI job replacement, we could see unemployment rates we‚Äôve never seen before.
This would lead to poverty and homelessness we‚Äôve never seen before.
And with a 10 year moratorium, states would have no way to regulate and make laws to protect people.
The people are who matter to me.
My children in their 20‚Äôs and their future children are who matter to me, and all of their generations.
Once many human jobs are replaced, who is paying these unemployed people?
How do they feed their families?
The economy will collapse.
And when they are no longer paying federal and state taxes because they can‚Äôt, how will that affect government funding?
The future is unknown and I believe in order to best lookout for people I‚Äôve sworn an oath to serve, I must defend federalism.
Besides this AI clause in the One Big Beautiful Bill doesn‚Äôt belong in the bill. That bill is supposed to be the president‚Äôs campaign promises, which are taxes, energy, and very much needed border security and deportations. 
Poison pills kill great bills.
Republicans must address AI separately with sincere diligent efforts instead of the typical tricks of shoving a 19 year federalism moratorium in a big thousand page bill. 
I want to see this done right to be good for all.

Name: Lee, Mike
text:
Are you tired of paying too much for medications?

I just introduced a bill to make your prescription drugs more affordable: The Biosimilar Red Tape Elimination Act.

‚ÄúBiosimilars‚Äù ‚Äì generic alternatives to name-brand medications ‚Äì have the potential to significantly reduce the cost of biologic drugs through increased competition.

Choosing biosimilars over their name-brand counterparts could save consumers an estimated $42.9 billion by 2027.

Americans deserve to hold this decision-making power, but red tape around biosimilars keeps them from being widely used. The FDA‚Äôs complex approval system has confused physicians, patients, and states about biosimilars‚Äô safety and efficacy.

Biosimilars must undergo extensive testing to prove they provide no meaningful difference from their name-brand version. Bringing a new biosimilar to market costs as much as $300 million and can take as long as 9 years.

Even after this approval, patients may not be able to access biosimilars because Congress created a separate designation: interchangeability. To be classified as truly ‚Äúinterchangeable‚Äù with the name-brand version, a biosimilar must undergo further testing called ‚Äúswitching studies.‚Äù This type of research has proven unnecessary for biosimilars, as it repeatedly shows no meaningful difference or relevant new data.

The Biosimilar Red Tape Elimination Act would remove these extra steps so that a biosimilar will immediately be classified as interchangeable upon its initial approval by the FDA. Foregoing unnecessary switching studies would no longer disqualify biosimilars as alternatives to their name-brand counterparts.

We need to give Americans the option to save billions on their medications and increase competition in the pharmaceutical market.

We should pass the Biosiliar Red Tape Elimination Act.

Read more here!üëáüëáüëá

Douglass was the first Black reporter admitted to the press gallery & his life/work embody the very best of America.

Name: Donalds, Byron
text:
Frederick Douglass was born into slavery in 1818. After courageously escaping bondage in 1838, he built a life dedicated to truth, liberty, and justice. He became a journalist in Rochester, New York, and launched The North Star using his own money, giving voice to the voiceless in the years before the Civil War.

He fought fiercely against slavery, championed equal rights and women‚Äôs suffrage, and became one of the most forceful orators in American history. During the Civil War, Douglass recruited Black soldiers, met with President Lincoln to advocate for equal pay and treatment, and worked to assist those escaping slavery.

Name: Donalds, Byron
text:
Thank you to @TransportGOP Chairman @RepSamGraves for your advancement of this resolution.

Thank you to @SpeakerJohnson, House leadership, and @HouseGOP co-sponsors: @RepBurgessOwens, @RepWPH, and @RepJames for your support of H.Res.137. https://t.co/ABP3Y4J0oT

Name: Donalds, Byron
text:
After his Rochester home was destroyed in a suspected arson attack, he moved to Washington, D.C. and became editor ‚Äî and later owner ‚Äî of the New National Era, which chronicled Black progress throughout the nation.

Douglass was the first Black reporter admitted to the Capitol press galleries. From 1871 to 1875, he reported on House and Senate action, keeping the African American community informed during Reconstruction after the 13th, 14th, and 15th Amendments. He spent countless hours writing and studying in the House Press Gallery.

Even after his tenure in the gallery, he returned often to the Capitol.

The right to peacefully protest must be protected. From Sacramento to Los Angeles, thousands of people are exercising their First Amendment right to protest the Trump Administration‚Äôs actions that are separating families and instilling fear in immigrant communities.

These protests have been overwhelmingly peaceful. But a small number of agitators have co-opted this moment to commit unacceptable acts of violence‚Äîincluding attacking police officers and setting fires. I want to be clear: I condemn these violent agitators and they must be prosecuted.

This moment calls for leadership that calms tensions‚Äînot escalates them. I know we can both protect public safety and uphold the rights guaranteed by our Constitution.

Unfortunately, President Trump has chosen escalation. The unprecedented deployment of active-duty Marines paired with mass ICE raids and use of tear gas in civilian areas represents a clear abuse of federal power that undermines civil liberties, destabilizes communities, and erodes public trust.

Federal, state, and local leaders should be working in partnership to restore calm, protect the rights of demonstrators, and uphold the constitutional principles that define our democracy. Name: Welch, Peter
text:
I‚Äôm deeply troubled by the rise of antisemitism in America in the wake of the conflict in Gaza. Statistics show a sharp uptick in hate crimes against Jewish folks in America since October 2023. Those include hate crime incidents in my own state of Vermont, the tragic murder of two Israeli embassy workers in Washington, D.C., and now an attack on a peaceful assembly for hostages held by Hamas in Colorado.

No one deserves to be discriminated against because of who they are. Antisemitism is wrong. Islamophobia is wrong. I've traveled to both Israel and Palestine. I've met with Israelis who want the conflict to end, who believe that Netanyahu's actions are harmful and won't make their country safer. I've met with Palestinians who denounce Hamas and mourn the loss of Israelis along with the tens of thousands of civilians killed in Gaza.

I‚Äòve been one of the most outspoken Senators against what I believe has been a harmful war strategy by Netanyahu. I was one of the first Senators to call for a ceasefire in the months following Hamas‚Äô horrendous attack on innocent people in Israel. I called for a ceasefire to prevent more loss of innocent life, free the remaining hostages, and to move toward a two-state solution.

I believe that Israel has a right to defend itself, but that Netanyahu has waged a reckless war campaign that disregards civilian life‚Äîincluding bombing aid workers and withholding humanitarian aid from reaching those who desperately need it.

Criticism of Prime Minister Netanyahu's actions doesn‚Äôt justify hate of our Jewish neighbors. Criticism of Hamas' actions doesn‚Äôt justify hate of our Palestinian neighbors.

I urge Americans to reject hate and respect each other. In Vermont, we have a deeply rooted value that regardless of differences, you give your neighbor a helping hand when they need it. We must come together and love each other.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
Antisemitism is surging globally, and it‚Äôs terrifying. We know the history of Jew hate - how it gains traction‚Ä¶slowly; and how it ends‚Ä¶very, very badly. We have 5,000 years of history to learn from and we need folks to take this seriously.

Some facts on antisemitism and the legislation to combat it üßµüëáüèº

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
This is legislation that has been worked on for years, and should pass with unanimous, bipartisan support.

Why is it controversial? A few reasons‚Ä¶

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
Trump‚Äôs actions on campuses have not helped. 

Campuses have become hotbeds of antisemitism that have sparked a debate about where the line between protecting the rights and freedoms of Jews and free speech is. 

But if he wants to fight antisemitism, he would work with groups like the American Jewish Committee (@AJCGlobal) that partners with organizations on how to identify and combat antisemitism without infringing on anyone‚Äôs 1st amendment rights.
https://t.co/8krOY2KnYr

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
The history of Jews is a history of being included and succeeding and it‚Äôs almost always followed by periods of exclusion, expulsion and, of course, mass murder.

It‚Äôs really important to teach people, especially students, what antisemitism is and isn‚Äôt, and how important it is to work together to combat antisemitism.

That‚Äôs what the Antisemitism Awareness Act does.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
It uses the International Holocaust Remembrance Alliance‚Äôs (@TheIHRA) working definition for antisemitism but nowhere in the bill does it punish people for this antisemitism. It is only used to evaluate the intent of existing crimes.

Here is a quick summary of the definition, which I hope folks readüëáüèº
https://t.co/iJwjvubrEC

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
Trump‚Äôs actions have had a chilling effect on free speech.

But this legislation doesn‚Äôt curb free speech.

Despite what you may hear online, the Antisemitism Awareness Act does not infringe on free speech. It does say that some things are antisemitic, which is pretty basic stuff, but it doesn‚Äôt outlaw anyone‚Äôs 1st amendment rights.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
This is about giving people the tools to learn about antisemitism, what it is at its core, and how it is often expressed around the world. It is education and awareness, not punishment.

The bill emphasizes:
‚û°Ô∏èAwareness and understanding
‚û°Ô∏èReversing the normalization of antisemitism through education
‚û°Ô∏èExpanding communication and collaboration.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
The bill requires colleges to use this definition in building out trainings and teachings that help to combat antisemitism. That‚Äôs it. 

It doesn‚Äôt punish any speech or stop anyone from being hateful.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
Whether any of us want to admit it, antisemitism is alive and well all across the political spectrum ‚Äì and across the world. 

Some on the Right like to spread the lie that Jews killed Jesus, which is the kind of blood libel that gets Jews killed.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
The bill allows for criticism of policies or actions of the Israeli government, which is exactly how it should be.

Israelis criticize their government and, unlike so many other countries in the Middle East, are allowed to protest their government openly. Anti-Zionism is different from being critical of the Israeli government. Anti-Zionism is the position that Israel should not be allowed to exist as a Jewish State.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
It‚Äôs so important for Marjorie Taylor Greene to maintain this blood libel, and to do so without consequences, that she opposes this bill.

Some on the Left suggest that the legislation prohibits criticism of Israel.

It does not.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
I‚Äôm a pro-Israel Jew who criticizes Israel, as we all do. I sometimes fly to Israel to be sure I look the Prime Minister in the eye and tell him my frustrations and disagreements with decisions he‚Äôs made. I believe it has had an impact.

I criticize Israel when I think the government is making mistakes. I do so in part because I desperately want to be part of a generation of leaders that finally achieves a durable peace for everyone in the Middle East - Israelis, Palestinians, Lebanese, Syrians, etc.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
Denying Jews self-determination, or anti-Zionism, is wrong. Denying Palestinians self-determination is also wrong, and why most pro-Israel advocates are also pro-Palestinian.

It‚Äôs the folks who believe that only one group deserves security and freedom that is problematic.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
I also push on Israel because I need it to succeed. Jews need a Jewish state. That is non-negotiable. Nearly all Jews live in two places - here and Israel. 

That‚Äôs not by choice.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
I would encourage my colleagues to stop politicizing this, on both sides. Our safety and wellbeing are at stake, and antisemitism should be a nonpartisan, non-controversial issue.

The fact that it‚Äôs not says a lot.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
Here‚Äôs an example that may help:

There are 100,000 Jews in Australia. Antisemitism is surging there, too. If they get kicked out, they only have one place they can go. Israel. That‚Äôs it. We‚Äôre not taking 100,000 Jews from Australia, nor is any other country. Except Israel.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
At today‚Äôs Oversight hearing with @SecDef Pete Hegseth, @thejointstaff Chairman General Dan Caine, and @DeptofDefense Comptroller Bryn MacDonnell, I raised serious concerns about the proposal to consolidate Army North and South and move the command out of San Antonio.

Army North plays a vital role supporting @DHSgov on the southern border with surveillance, logistics, engineering, and medical assistance. Relocating it risks undermining mission effectiveness at a time when 11,900 active-duty troops are deployed under Title 10 authority as part of Joint Task Force‚ÄìSouthern Border.

This decision would impact not just national security, but also our local economy. The military is San Antonio‚Äôs top employer, and the community has already invested $20M in new facilities to enhance its role as a hub for military medical missions. San Antonio also hosts the Sixteenth Air Force (Air Forces Cyber), a key component of our nation‚Äôs cyber defense. This move would disrupt military families who‚Äôve already relocated to support these critical missions.

San Antonio has the infrastructure, workforce, and strategic location to support our national defense. I‚Äôll continue fighting to keep these vital missions right here - close to the border they‚Äôre tasked with protecting.

I look forward to continuing these conversations to ensure our national security decisions strengthen, not weaken, border readiness and Texas communities. I‚Äôll continue working with our San Antonio delegation, and the entire Texas delegation, to keep these missions in place, protect our servicemembers and families, and ensure South Texas remains at the center of our national defense strategy.

Name: Rounds, Mike
text:
Here at Team Rounds, our former interns are doing some awesome things, and we want to highlight them! Meet Sara Hofer of Salem:

What did you learn in your internship that has helped you through the rest of your college career? 
‚ÄúOne thing I learned throughout the summer internship is adaptability and the value of asking questions. Senator Rounds‚Äô office has many constituent services and legislative responsibilities that ensure all tasks are done efficiently and on time. Adapting to situations, asking clarifying questions, and critically listening to staff and constituents‚Äô requests has helped me become a better student by encouraging me to grow in the comfort that not knowing everything right away is okay. Asking questions helps you better understand what is required of you to complete any task to the best of your ability, which has helped me throughout my entire college experience.‚Äù

Is there a memory from your internship that still sticks out to you? 
‚ÄúAlthough I made many great memories, some that stick out to me include the times I spent at different Senate Committee Hearings on Capitol Hill. These opportunities deepened my understanding of how the legislative branch of the government functions and deepened my appreciation for the work that Senators, specifically Senator Rounds, do for South Dakotans. Outside of the internship, exploring the Washington D.C. area over the summer was also one of my favorite parts of the summer.‚Äù

Name: Roy, Chip
text:
üö®Today, the House Judiciary Committee (@JudiciaryGOP) PASSED Rep. Roy‚Äôs FACE Act Repeal. 

Here are some common myths related to the FACE Act and why it must be repealed.

üßµTHREAD:

Name: Roy, Chip
text:
‚ùåFALSE: ‚ÄúWithout the FACE Act, there are no laws to protect churches or Pregnancy Resource Centers.‚Äù

‚úÖFACT: A repeal of the FACE Act still leaves in place a plethora of existing federal safeguards including:

- Interference with Commerce by Threats or Violence (18 U.S.C. ¬ß 1951)

- Damage to Religious Property or Obstruction of persons in Free Exercise of Religious Beliefs (18 U.S.C. ¬ß 247)

- Interstate Travel or Transportation to Aid in Racketeering Enterprises (18 U.S.C. ¬ß 1952)

While actions such as trespassing, obstructing, vandalism, and assault are already illegal in all 50 states.

Name: Roy, Chip
text:
‚ùåFALSE: ‚ÄúThe FACE Act equally protects Pregnancy Resource Centers & churches, just as it does abortion facilities.‚Äù

‚úÖFACT: Despite increased violence at Pregnancy Resource Centers, the Biden-Harris DOJ brought 92% of the FACE Act cases against pro-lifers, with a mere 8% targeting pro-abortion agitators.

There is no denying the data ‚Äì there has been an unequal application of the FACE Act.

Name: Roy, Chip
text:
‚ùåFALSE: ‚ÄúThe FACE Act helps deter bad actors from targeting abortion facilities, churches, & Pregnancy Resource Centers.‚Äù

‚úÖFACT: Violence against churches in America has increased by 800% since 2018 - an average of 39 attacks every month, coinciding with 96 recorded attacks on pregnancy resource centers since May 2022.

The FACE Act has clearly not deterred violence.

Name: Roy, Chip
text:
‚ùåFALSE: ‚ÄúThe FACE Act does not make felons out of 1st time offenders.‚Äù

‚úÖFACT: By coupling FACE Act violations with ‚ÄúConspiracy Against Rights‚Äù charges, the Biden Admin made felons out of Americans for peaceful acts such as sidewalk counseling or singing hymns.

With this law on the books, NO American is safe from political prosecution.

Name: Roy, Chip
text:
Don‚Äôt be fooled ‚Äì Congress MUST stop this weaponization by passing H.R 589, repealing the FACE Act once and for all.

END üßµ

Name: Crow, Jason
text: 2/ During my time in the military, I served in both National Guard and elite active-duty units (Rangers/paratroopers). I understand the training, authorities, and capabilities of military units.

text: 3/ Our military is highly skilled, but receives very little training in law enforcement and domestic disturbance. Military forces are trained and organized for high-intensity combat operations.

Name: Crow, Jason
text: 5/ In 1932, the Army was used to clear out a protest encampment of veterans seeking benefits. It ended in violence and damaged the reputation of the Army.

Name: Crow, Jason
text: 4/ Sending military personnel with combat equipment and heavy weapons into tense domestic situations rarely deescalates. We have often seen deadly consequences and the erosion of public trust.

Name: Crow, Jason
text:

Bottom line: these incidents not only resulted in deaths but eroded trust in our military.

PA-1 families depend on and deserve strong, reliable care‚Äîand that starts with supporting the people and facilities that provide it.

Great meeting today with the @PHCA_Cares and local leaders from CommuniCare and @SaberHCG ‚Äîwho operate Silver Lake Healthcare in Bristol and Langhorne Gardens and Statesman in Langhorne.

We discussed the urgent challenges facing our nursing homes including workforce shortages, rising costs, and the growing strain on care delivery, and how I can continue to support them. 

Grateful to Gabrielle Charnowitz, VP of Government Affairs & Strategic Development at CommuniCare; Cody Meenan, Regional VP of Operations at Saber Healthcare; Beth Beiler, Regional Director of Business Development at Saber Healthcare; and Zach Shamberg, President & CEO of PHCA for their partnership and leadership. I look forward to continuing our work together to look forward to continuing our work to advance solutions that protect our seniors, support our caregivers, and strengthen care across our community.
